OS</a>, those include:&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"m=
argin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"colo=
r: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">Quality oversig=
ht of the company as a whole (performance reviews, independent voices, back=
ground checks, etc.)</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; ms=
o-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0;">The SDLC (software development lifecycle) is tr=
ansparent, trackable, and controlled (issue tracking, unit testing, version=
 control, etc.)</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-spe=
cial-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0;">Your application and underlying infrastructure are s=
ecure and monitored (encryption, logging, APM, vulnerability scans, etc.)</=
p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bull=
et;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0;">You&#8217;ve implemented access controls for internal services and Sa=
aS (de-provisioning accounts, 2FA, malware detection, etc.)</p></li></ul><p=
 style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1=
em 0;">A lot of these things are best practices anyway; SOC 2 just makes yo=
u prove and document everything. First, startups typically get SOC 2 Type I=
, which is just a snapshot in time, and then get SOC 2 Type II, which is au=
dited over 3-12 months, to satisfy customers&#8217; compliance requirements=
=2E Plus, they need to get <strong>recer=
tified annually</strong>, all signed =
off on by an auditor.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">And that&#8217;s just SOC 2. There&=
#8217;s also ISO 27001, published jointly by the International Organization=
 for Standardisation and the International Electrotechnical Commission, whi=
ch was recently revised in 2013. ISO 27001 has ~75-85% overlap with SOC 2, =
but adds on a few information security-specific requirements.&nbsp;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em=
 0;">If you deal with credit cards, there&#8217;s Payment Card Industry (PC=
I) Standards. Healthcare has the Health Insurance Portability and Accountab=
ility Act (HIPAA). The Federal government has the Federal Risk and Authoriz=
ation Management Program (FedRAMP), which is so onerous -- it takes about <=
strong>two years and $1 million to complete</strong> -- that less than 300 =
vendors are FedRAMP certified. The Department of Defense recently introduce=
d the Cybersecurity Maturity Model Certification (CMMC), its attempt to mak=
e it easier and more accessible to sell software to federal agencies. The a=
verage CMMC audit costs $10-30k instead of $1 million.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Al=
l of that sounds like a ton of work, and it is. It all sounds bad and overl=
y onerous, but it&#8217;s not. <strong>Standards actually level the playing=
 field</strong> and make it possible for companies to sell into enterprises=
 and other startups more quickly and cheaply than ever before.</p><h3 style=
=3D"-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialias=
